text: Your Wednesday Evening BriefingHere’s what you need to know at the end of the day.
The Modern Love PodcastConfronting race on the first date.

The shutdown in the nation’s largest school system was prompted by the city reaching a 3 percent test positivity rate over a seven-day rolling average.It is perhaps the most significant setback for New York’s recovery since the spring, when the city was a global epicenter of the outbreak.
A meal at the French Laundry? A junket to Maui? California’s Democratic leaders have put strict virus measures in place. If only they would follow them.
“I don’t want to do this.” Gov. Kim Reynolds joined a wave of Republican governors issuing new mask orders as her state faces a spiraling crisis.
The company said it planned to apply for emergency approval from the Food and Drug Administration “within days.”
The surge in coronavirus cases worldwide is helping researchers measure more quickly how well their vaccines protect against Covid-19.

Mexico, Outraged at Arrest of Ex-Official, Threatened to Toss U.S. AgentsThe threat to expel federal drug agents from the country appears to have worked: The U.S. has dropped charges against a former Mexican defense minister.
Central American migrants seeking asylum in the United States were apprehended last year by Border Patrol in Penitas, Texas. Adrees Latif/Reuters

When Michigan Republicans Refused to Certify Votes, It Wasn’t NormalAfter Republican officials initially refused to certify votes, voters were left wondering: Could the results of a free election be blocked that easily?

Kevin McCarthy, House Minority Leader, Doesn’t Think Trump Is Going AwayThe California Republican believes his party’s victories in 2020 came thanks to President Trump, not in spite of him: “He brought turnout.”
Lindsey Wasson for The New York Times
